Here's a concise JavaScript `debounce` function example:

Explanation: A `debounce` function prevents a function from being called too frequently by delaying its execution until a specified time has passed since the last call.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeoutId;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}

// Example usage:
function search(query) {
  console.log(`Searching for: ${query}`);
}

const debouncedSearch = debounce(search, 300);

debouncedSearch("first");  // May not execute
debouncedSearch("second"); // May not execute
debouncedSearch("third");  // Only this call will execute after 300ms
```
